  <subsection xml:id="subsec-Commission-and-percentage-commission">
    <title>Commission and percentage commission.</title>
    <p>
      <m>{\color{blue} \text{Commission}}</m> is the amount of money paid 
      to a salesperson based on the value of goodsand services he or she sells.
    </p>
    <p>
      <m>{\color{blue} \text{A percentage commission}}</m> is a fee calculated as a fixed percentage of the total 
      sales or transaction value. 
      It is commonly used in sales, marketing, and brokerage.
    </p>

    <activity>
      <p>
        <m>{\color{green} \text{Work in groups}}</m>
      </p>
      <p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
              Read the story below and answer the question that follows.
            </p>
            <p>
              Mzee Morara owns a large motor vehicle firm. He imports cars 
              and sells them locally. He has employed Zawadi and Onyimbo to sell 
              the cars on his behalf. The employees have a basic salary of 
              <m>sh. \, 20 \, 000</m> each. They are also paid an extra amount of money 
              depending on the value of cars sold. Every month, Zawadi and Onyimbo 
              earn more money than their basic salary. In July, they earned a total 
              of <m>sh. \, 30 \, 000</m> each. They walked home happy than everbefore.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </p>
      <p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              How much extra money did Zawadi and Onyimbo earn in July?
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>What is the name of the extra money they earned?</li>
          <li>Share your work with other learners in your class.</li>
          
        </ol>
      </p>
    </activity>

    <activity>
      <p>
        <m>{\color{green} \text{Work in pairs}}</m>
      </p>
      <p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              Movine is a sales agent in a publising company. The table below 
              shows the commision he received in one week from the sale of books.
            </p>
            <tabular halign="left" bottom="medium" top="medium"  right="medium" left="medium" >
              <row header="yes">
                <cell>Weeks</cell>
                <cell>Value of goods sold</cell>
                <cell>commission </cell>
                <cell>Percentage commission <m>(\frac{Commission}{Total \, sales} \times 100\%)</m></cell>
              </row>
              <row>
                <cell>Week 1</cell>
                <cell><m>sh. \, 80 \, 000</m></cell>
                <cell><m>sh. \, 8\, 000</m></cell>
                <cell></cell>
              </row>
              <row>
                <cell>Week 2</cell>
                <cell><m>sh. \, 75 \, 000</m></cell>
                <cell><m>sh. \, 7 \, 500</m></cell>
                <cell></cell>
              </row>
              <row>
                <cell>Week 3</cell>
                <cell><m>sh. \, 92 \, 000</m></cell>
                <cell><m>sh. \, 9 \, 200</m></cell>
                <cell></cell>
              </row>
              <row>
                <cell>Week 4</cell>
                <cell><m>sh. \, 87 \, 700</m></cell>
                <cell><m>sh. \, 8 \, 770</m></cell>
                <cell></cell>
              </row>
            </tabular>
          </li>
          <li>Complete the table by working out the percentage commission.</li>
          <li>Share your work with other learners in class.</li>
        </ol>
      </p>
      <p>
        <m>{\color{green} \text{Learning point}}</m>
      </p>
      <p>
        <em>Most companies employ people to market their goods. 
        These people are paid some money depending on the value of the 
        goods sold. This amount of money is called <m>{\color{blue} \text{commission}}</m></em>. 
        Some salespeople are paid a monthly sallary together with the commision.
      </p>
      <p>
        <me>Percentage\, commision \, = \frac{Comission}{Value \, of \, goods\, sold} \times 100\%</me>
      </p>
      <p>
        Follow this link for more activity <url href="https://youtu.be/YSWpoyEhYzA"></url>
      </p>
    </activity>
    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          A certain campany gives its salespeople commission of <m> sh. \, 60</m> for every  <m> sh. \, 800</m> 
          worth of goods they sell. In two days, Nyakiambi who is an employee in the company sold goods worth  <m> sh. \, 96 \, 000 </m>. 
          How much commisiion did she earn?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Total value of goods <m>= sh. \, 96 \, 000</m>
        </p>
        <p>
          Commission on <m> sh. \, 800</m> sale <m> = sh. \, 60</m>
        </p>
        <p>
          Therefore commision on <m>sh. \, 96 \, 000</m> is,
        </p>
        <p>
          <md>
            <mrow> = \amp \frac{sh. \, 96 \, 000}{sh. \, 800}  \times sh. \, 60</mrow>
             <mrow> =\amp sh. \,7\, 200 </mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
        <p>
          The commision that Nyakiambi earned was <m>{\color{blue} sh. \,7\, 200  }</m>
        </p>

      </solution>
    </example>
    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Baya received <m>sh. \, 20\, 000</m> as a commission after selling 
          a car for <m>sh. \, 400\, 000</m>. What percentage commission was he given?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <hint>
        <p>
          Use the formular <m>Percentage \,commission = \frac{Commission}{Value \, of \, goods \, sold} \times 100\%</m>
        </p>
      </hint>
      <solution>
        <p>
          The value of goods sold <m>=sh. \, 400\, 000</m>
        </p>
        <p>
          Commission on sale <m>= sh. \, 20\, 000</m>
        </p>
        <p>
          <md>
            <mrow> percentage \,commission =\amp  \frac{Commission}{Value \, of \, goods \, sold} \times 100\% </mrow>
            <mrow> =\amp \frac{20 \, 000}{400 \, 000}  \times 100\%</mrow>
            <mrow> =\amp 5\% </mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
        <p>
          She was given a percentage commision of <m>{\color{blue} 5\%  }</m>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Abdi, a salesperson, is paid a commission of <m>10\%</m> of the value 
          of his sales, In one month, he sold goods worth <m>sh.\, 180 \, 000</m>. 
          How much commission did he earn?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <hint>
        <p>
          Commission=<m>\text{Value of goods sold} \times \text{Commision rate} </m>
        </p>
      </hint>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Commision rate on the value of sale <m>= 10\%</m>
        </p>
        <p>
          value of goods sold is worth <m>sh. \, 180\,000</m>
        </p>
        <p>
          <md>
            <mrow> Commission=\amp \text{Value of goods sold} \times \text{Commision rate} </mrow>
            <mrow> =\amp \frac{10}{100}  \times sh. \, 180\,000</mrow>
            <mrow> =\amp sh.\, 18 \, 000 </mrow>
          </md>
          
          
        </p>
        <p>
          Abdi, earned <m>{\color{blue} sh.\, 18 \, 000 }</m> commission.
        </p>

      </solution>

    </example>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          A saleslady is paid a basic salary of <m>sh. \,10\,000</m> and 
          <m>10\%</m> commission of the value of goods sold. In one month, she 
          sold goods worth <m>sh. \, 200\, 000</m>. What were her total earnings that 
          month?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <hint>
        <p>
          Total earnings is the basic salary together with commission.
        </p>
        <p>
          <m>Total\, earnings= Basic \, salary + Commission </m>
        </p>
      </hint>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Commision rate <m>= 10\%</m>
        </p>
        <p>
          Basic salary <m>= sh. \, 10 \, 000</m>
        </p>
        <p>
          Goods sold <m>= sh. \, 200\, 000</m>
        </p>
        <p>
          Commission paid <m>= 10\% \text{of the valu of goods sold}</m>
        </p>
        <p>
          <md>
            <mrow> =\amp  \frac{10}{100} \times sh . \, 200\, 000</mrow>
            <mrow> =\amp {\color{green} sh. \,20 \, 000  }</mrow>
            
          </md>
        </p>
        <p>
          <md>
            <mrow> \text{Total earnings} =\amp \text{Basic salary} + \text{commission} </mrow>
            <mrow> =\amp sh. \, 10 \, 000 + sh.\, 20\, 000 </mrow>
            <mrow> =\amp {\color{pink} sh. \,30 \, 000  } </mrow>
          </md>
          
        </p>
        <p>
          The tatal earnings that month was <m> {\color{blue} sh. \,30 \, 000  }</m>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

  </subsection>
  


  <subsection xml:id="subsec-Bills">
    <title>Bills</title>
    <introduction>
      <p>
        A bill shows the various items sold, their 
        quantities, the price per unit item and cost.
      </p>
      <p>
        It acts as a proof of the payment made or 
        received during a business transaction.
      </p>
      <p>
        There are different types of bills such as; <m> {\color{green} \text{Eectricity bills, telephone bills, 
        water bills, house bills, hotel bills, among others.}}</m>
      </p>
      <p>
        <m> {\color{black} \text{Components of a bill} }</m>
      </p>
      <p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              A bill always has the <m> {\color{green} \text{Name of the shop }}</m> mentioned on top.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li><m> {\color{green}\text{A unique number }}</m> is given to each of the bills. 
          it is called <m> {\color{green} \text{bill number }}</m> or the <m> {\color{green} \text{serial number }}</m> of a bill. 
          It help us find that particular bill easily. <m> {\color{black} \text{No two bill of the same 
          shop will have the same bill number.} }</m></li>
          <li>The date mentioned on the bill is called the <m> {\color{green} \text{Date of purchase. }}</m></li>
          <li>The <m> {\color{green} \text{list of items }}</m> purchased are always given under 
          the item column.</li>
          <li><m> {\color{green} \text{Quantity }}</m> is the total number of each item bought. 
          Quantity can either be in <m> {\color{green} \text{numbers}}</m> or <m> {\color{green} \text{weights.}}</m> For example 
          , one notebook or <m>1</m> kilogram of rice. In this case, the notebook 
          is quantified in numbers, and rice is quantified in weights.</li>
          <li>The <m> {\color{green} \text{cost }}</m> of each item or the rate 
          of each item is the <m> {\color{green} \text{original price }}</m> of each item.</li>
          <li><m> {\color{green} \text{Amount }}</m> to be paid for each item is 
          quantity multiplied by the rate of each item.</li>
          <li>The <m> {\color{green} \text{total amount }}</m> to be paid for the entire purchase is 
          the <m> {\color{green} \text{addition of amounts to be paid }}</m> for each of the items.</li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </introduction>






